Preheat your oven to 220°C. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Roughly chop the @closed cup mushrooms{150}(roughly chopped). Thinly slice the @portobello mushrooms{2%portobello}(thinly sliced). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated). Pull the @thyme{1}(leaves pulled off stalks) leaves off their stalks (discard the stalks). Drain and rinse the @black beans{1}(drained and rinsed). Put half the blackbeans in a #bowl{} and roughly mash with a #fork{}. Set aside.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{a drizzle} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once the oil is hot, add the red onion and a pinch of @salt{pinch}, @sugar{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Cook until softened, ~{5-6%minutes}, stirring occasionally. Once cooked, remove from the pan to a bowl and pop your pan back on medium-high heat. Add a drizzle of @oil{a drizzle} and the portobello mushrooms. Add a pinch of salt and pepper and stir-fry the mushrooms until slightly softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the chopped mushrooms, half the thyme and more oil if needed. Stir-fry the mushrooms until golden, ~{3-5%minutes}. Stir in the garlic and red onion, cook for ~{1%minute}, then add the black beans (whole and crushed) and the @water{1%tbsp}. Bring to the boil, stir everything together, simmer until the water has completely evaporated, ~{3-5%minutes}. Remove from the heat, taste and add salt and pepper if you feel it needs it.

Add the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g} to the mixture in the pan and stir together until combined. Set aside to cool down a little. Meanwhile, trim the tops from the @chantenay carrots{250}(tops trimmed and halved lengthways) and halve lengthways. Pop the carrots on a #baking tray{}, drizzle with @oil{a drizzle}, sprinkle over the remaining thyme and a pinch of salt and pepper. Set aside and get your washing up done for a couple of mins (while the mixture cools).

Unroll the @puff pastry sheet{1}(unrolled) onto a large baking tray (on the baking paper it comes with) and spoon the mushroom mixture along one half of the long side, leaving a 2cm gap down the long side and both ends. Fold the other half of the pastry over the mixture to enclose, gently press down the edges of the pastry with the back of a fork to seal the parcel on all 3 sides. Make a small hole in the top with a fork. Roast on the top shelf of your oven until the pastry is golden, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Add your baking tray of carrots on the middle shelf to cook for ~{20-25%minutes} too. Once cooked, remove the wellington from the oven and slice into 3 slices per person. Serve on plates with your roasted carrots alongside and enjoy!